The Lorentz factor of a monster plasmoid in the rest frame of the jet γp can be estimated using the luminosity contrast between the minute-scale-flare to the envelope emission, γp = δp/Γj ~ 2.2. The Doppler factor of the monster plasmoid δp is a function of jet’s Lorentz factor Γj, the monster plasmoid’s Lorentz factor in the rest frame of the jet γp, and the angle of the monster plasmoid with respect to the jet’s motion and the observer’s angle of sight. Here, we adopt δp ~ 1.1Γjγp which is similar as used by Giannios et al.35. Considering Γj ~ 35 which is required to avoid pair production in the emission zone due to low-energy synchrotron photons and also to avoid a super Eddington jet, we compute the monster plasmoid’s Doppler factor δp ~ 85. The emission from the reconnection region as a whole can account for the observed envelope emission. The corresponding envelope timescales (rise time of envelope emission tenv ~ 1.2 ×  105 s) provide a characteristic size l′=tenvΓjϵc/(1+z)~8.2×1015\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
